The parent provided car seat is appropriate to their infant's weight and height. Despite proper positioning,    there is still slack in the harness straps. (You can pinch the harness strap at the collarbone). Discharge is  tomorrow and they are unwilling to provide another car seat. You educate the parents (and document)      about the danger and liability in using the seat with slack in the harness straps. They sign the CSC statement of understanding saying "We'll be careful". What do you do?
answer_text: A)  Place blankets under and behind the infant to take up the slack in the harness straps then begin the car seat challenge.

question_text: The parent provided car seat is appropriate to their infant's weight and height. Despite proper positioning,    there is still slack in the harness straps. You educate the parents (and document)      about the danger and liability in using the seat with slack in the harness straps. They sign the CSC statement of understanding saying "We'll be careful". What do you do?
answer_text: B) Contact Care Coordination for a DCFS referral as these parents are knowingly endangering their    infant.

question_text: The parent provided car seat is appropriate to their infant's weight and height. Despite proper positioning,    there is still slack in the harness straps. (You can pinch the harness strap at the collarbone). Discharge is  tomorrow and they are unwilling to provide another car seat. You educate the parents (and document)      about the danger and liability in using the seat with slack in the harness straps. They sign the CSC statement of understanding saying "We'll be careful". What do you do?
answer_text: C) Have the parent initial both statements and then sign the Release of Liability for Child Safety Seat  (#NH0725) and proceed with the car seat challenge.

question_text: The parent provided car seat is appropriate to their infant's weight and height. Despite proper positioning,    there is still slack in the harness straps. What do you do?
answer_text: D) Check the "YES" box for noncompliance and document that the parents verbalize understanding of the danger of the observed noncompliance with the manufacturer's instructions -slack in  the harness straps- in the comments section of the EMR and proceed with the car seat challenge.

The infant is positioned with its back flat against the back of the car seat, yet the infants shoulders are still slightly (") below the lowest shoulder harness slot. The harness straps are snug (pass the "pinch test"). The parent has signed the CSC statement and is unwilling to bring   another car seat. What do you do?
answer_text: A)  The straps are snug so there is not a compliance issue. Begin the car seat challenge

question_text: The shoulder harness straps are in the lowest position on the car seat. The infant is positioned with its back flat against the back of the car seat, yet the infants shoulders are still slightly (") below the lowest shoulder harness slot. The harness straps are snug (pass the "pinch test"). The parent has signed the CSC statement and is unwilling to bring   another car seat. What do you do?
answer_text: B)  Check the manufacturer's instructions. If the harness height is allowed to be slightly above the shoulders, check the "NO" box for compliance issues and begin the car seat challenge but note that the harness height was allowed to be above the   shoulders in the comments box.

question_text: The shoulder harness straps are in the lowest position on the car seat. The infant is positioned with its back flat against the back of the car seat, yet the infants shoulders are still slightly (") below the lowest shoulder harness slot. The harness straps are snug (pass the "pinch test"). The parent has signed the CSC statement and is unwilling to bring   another car seat. What do you do?
answer_text: C)  Check the manufacturer's instructions. If the manufacturer does NOT allow  the shoulder harness to be above the  infants shoulders, check the "YES" box, describe the non-compliance issue (harness height above the infants shoulders),   indicate that the parents verbalized understanding of the danger of the misuse in the  comment box in the EMR and education record, then begin the car seat challenge

What is the current AAP recommendation for how long an infant should ride rear-facing in a child safety seat?
answer_text: A) The infant should ride rear-facing until it is both #20 lbs. and one year past the original due date

question_text: What is the current AAP recommendation for how long an infant should ride rear-facing in a child safety seat?
answer_text: B) The infant should ride rear-facing until it is either 2 years old or #30 lbs.

question_text: What is the current AAP recommendation for how long an infant should ride rear-facing in a child safety seat?
answer_text: C) The infant should ride rear-facing until the harness straps are at the highest level on a rear-facing seat

question_text: What is the current AAP recommendation for how long an infant should ride rear-facing in a child safety seat?
answer_text: D) The infant should ride rear facing until they reach the highest weight or height allowed by their child safety seat's manufacturer

question_text: It is the day of discharge. The parents did not bring the car seat base and are unable to go back home for the base. Can you do the car seat challenge without the base?
answer_text: A) NO - if the car seat has a base you must do the test with the car seat in the base to verify the correct angle

question_text: It is the day of discharge. The parents did not bring the car seat base and are unable to go back home for the base. Can you do the car seat challenge without the base?
answer_text: B) YES - as long the car seat label indicates the car seat can be used without  the base, you are able to simulate the angle as recommended by the manufacturer, and you document that the base was not used in the comments box  in the EMR

question_text: The infant has a desaturation to 89% for 5 seconds after 40 minutes of the car seat challenge. How do you document this?

question_text: The infant has a desaturation to 89% for 5 seconds after 40 minutes of the car seat challenge. How do you document this?

answer_text: D)  Events outside the parameters during car seat challenge are documented in events box under "Other"  but this is not a failed car seat  challenge

What are the "fail" criteria during the 90 - 120 minute car seat challenge?
answer_text: A) A heart rate  < 80 for greater than 10 seconds, OR oxygen saturation < 88% for greater than 10 seconds; OR apnea for greater than 20 seconds

question_text: What are the "fail" criteria during the 90 - 120 minute car seat challenge?
answer_text: B)  A heart rate < 80 OR an oxygen saturation < 90% regardless of the duration

question_text: What are the "fail" criteria during the 90 - 120 minute car seat challenge?
answer_text: C)  Any oxygen saturation < 85%, regardless of duration

question_text: What are the "fail" criteria during the 90 - 120 minute car seat challenge?
answer_text: D) Apnea for greater than 20 seconds OR oxygen saturation < 90% for greater than 10 seconds OR heart rate less than 80 for greater than 10 seconds

question_text:
Scenario:
75 yo female admitted through the ED. She states that she has been having diarrhea at home off and on for the last week. She describes her "diarrhea" as loose stools that she had once or twice a day 3 times last week. A c-diff test is ordered on admission. 3 days after admission there is no documentation of a stool. Per NSH policy the lab cancelled the order for the specimen after 2 days. The next day she was given miralax due to constipation. She had two liquid stools on the day the miralax was ordered.
The nurse should:
answer_text: A.	Send the stool for c-diff testing and place patient on modified contact isolation.
course_name: FY2021 C. DIFF ANNUAL EDUCATION: PATIENT CARE

You are taking care of a total care patient. What are some of the interventions you will use to protect this patient's skin from breakdown? Select all that apply.
a. Keep skin clean and moisturized.

question_text: A 32 year old pregnant woman is diagnosed with a DVT. The physician begins enoxaparin (Lovenox) 1mg/kg SQ q12h.  What monitoring should be considered?
answer_text: a.	Check anti-Xa peak 1 hour after the first dose. Her goal range is 0.6-1 int. units/mL

question_text: B.302 Reporting Adverse Medical Device Incidents PURPOSE:  To describe the process for reporting Adverse Medical Device Incidents. In compliance with Safe Medical Devices Act of 1990, it is the policy of the clinical transplant program to report all deaths, serious illness, or injury to either the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and/or the manufacturer that are sustained by a patient at the clinical program and are caused or suspected to have been caused by a medical device. This policy applies to any individual who discovers, witnesses, or is notified of a suspected medical device incident. answer_text: a.  Insert a Foley catheter: she is probably bleeding due to a full bladder.

question_text: Reference:  Interdiciplinary Professional Practice P&P Clinical Guidelines CG-04.00 Diabetic Clinical Guidelines  Your post partum patient's blood glucose is 65. The patient denies any symptoms of hypoglycemia. What should you do?
answer_text: a.  Give 4 ounces of orange juice with sugar added.

question_text: Reference:  Interdiciplinary Professional Practice P&P Clinical Guidelines CG-04.00 Diabetic Clinical Guidelines  Your post partum patient's blood glucose is 65. The patient denies any symptoms of hypoglycemia. What should you do?
answer_text: b.  No action is required as the patient's skin is warm and dry and she denies any symptoms of hypoglycemia.

question_text: Reference:  Interdiciplinary Professional Practice P&P Clinical Guidelines CG-04.00 Diabetic Clinical Guidelines  Your post partum patient's blood glucose is 65. The patient denies any symptoms of hypoglycemia. What should you do?
answer_text: c.  Give 15 grams of glucose (Glutose, or 4 ounces of juice or milk), recheck glucose in 15 minutes, and notify MD.

question_text: Reference:  Interdiciplinary Professional Practice P&P Clinical Guidelines CG-04.00 Diabetic Clinical Guidelines  Your post partum patient's blood glucose is 65. The patient denies any symptoms of hypoglycemia. What should you do?
answer_text: d.  Tell patient to call for any symptoms of hypoglycemia, and tell her that you will need to recheck her glucose level in one hour.
